Question 1

Is there a general trend (e.g., increasing or decreasing) for life expectancy across time? Is this trend linear? (answering this qualitatively from the plot, you will do a statistical analysis of this question shortly)

Here is my answer:

The general trend is linear. We can see that the general trend for life expectancy is positively increasing in a steady manner over time.

Violin Plot

A slightly different way of making the same plot is looking at the distribution of life expectancy across countries as it changes over time:

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=factor(year), y=lifeExp)) +
    geom_violin() +
    labs(title="Life Expectancy Over Time",
         x = "Year",
         y = "Life Expectancy")

This type of plot is called a violin plot, and it displays the distribution of the variable in the y-axis for each value of the variable in the x-axis.

Question 2

How would you describe the distribution of life expectancy across countries for individual years? Is it skewed, or not? Unimodal or not? Symmetric around its center?

Here is my answer:

In the early years (1952-1967), the distribution for life expectancy is skewed towards the lower bottom number of years; it’s skewed towards 40-45 years. In the mid and later years (1972-2007), the distribution for life expectancy is skewed towards the upper top number of years; skewed towards 70-80 years and gradually increases over time, skewing towards the highest number of years at 2007. The distribution is unimodal part of the time. In the mid years (1962-1972), it’s not very clear where the mode is, which means it could be bimodal for those years. It is also not symmetric around it’s center.

I have a feeling that I WOULD reject the null hypothesis of no relationship. If we look at the graph, there IS a relationship; it’s a positive one, with life expectancy increasing over time.

Exercise 2

Fit a linear regression model using the lm function for life expectancy vs. year (as a continuous variable). Use the broom::tidy to look at the resulting model.

gapminder %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=lifeExp)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm) +
  labs(title="Life Expectancy Over Time",
         x = "Year",
         y = "Life Expectancy")

glm <- lm(lifeExp~year, data=gapminder)
tidy(glm)

Question 7

Do you reject the null hypothesis of no relationship between year and life expectancy? Why?

Here is my answer:

I would reject the null hypothesis of no relationship, for the simple reason that in our dataframe, there IS a relationship; it is a postive one that indicates that life expectancy increases per year. We can also see that the p-value is very close to zero, which will allow us to reject the null hypothesis of no relationship since the p-value is the probability that we observed our results given that the null hypothesis is true; so a small p-value allows us to reject the null hypothesis.

Question 13

Is the interaction model significantly better than the year-only model? Why?

Here is my answer:

I’d say that the interaction model has a much smaller sum sq of residuals than the year only model, which would indicate that the interaction model is MARGINALLY better than the year-only model. This makes sense because different continents have different quality of life so the life expectancy would improve at different rates based on that. Additionally, the f-values also indicate that the interaction model is better, because the interaction model has higher f-scores than the year-only model which indicates that the interaction model more strongly rejects the null hypothesis. However, since the p-values for both models are so close to zero already, it’s difficult to say if they are SIGNIFICANTLY better. But they are definitely marginally better.

The prediction task we are going to answer is:

“Can we predict if mortgage affordability will increase or decrease a year from now”

Specifically, we will do this for the last observation in the dataset (quarter 4 (Q4) of 2017). To create the outcome we will predict we will compare affordability for Q4 of 2017 and to Q4 of 2016 and label it as up or down depending on the sign of the this difference. Let’s create the outcome we want to predict (again, copy this bit of code to your submission):

outcome_df <- tidy_afford %>%
  mutate(yq = quarter(time, with_year=TRUE)) %>%
  filter(yq %in% c("2016.4", "2017.4")) %>%
  dplyr::select(RegionID, RegionName, yq, affordability) %>%
  spread(yq, affordability) %>%
  mutate(diff = `2017.4` - `2016.4`) %>%
  mutate(Direction = ifelse(diff>0, "up", "down")) %>%
  dplyr::select(RegionID, RegionName, Direction)
outcome_df

predictor_df <- tidy_afford %>%

My Question

Is a random forest better than a decision tree?

Here is my discussion of the question:

I wanted to see if training over a random forest yields better predictions than a single decision tree. Since a random forest averages multiple decision trees, this question becomes a simple case of: Which produces better predictions: the average of many decision trees, or a single decision tree?

As noted in the notes, decision trees are used in classification problems where the outcome is categorical, which applies to this data as we are forecasting a categorical direction for our prediction (either up or down). The tree would partition for each categorical prediction into regions, which predict the majority class for training observations within region.

Using a decision tree has several good properties:

  • Decision trees are natural constructs, since the outcomes are categorical (Up, Down)
  • The models are invariant under transformations in the predictor space
  • Tree growth is efficient
  • Models go after interactions immediately
  • Multi-factor responses are easily dealt with

However, there are a couple problems:

  • Results can be variable
  • Simple trees do not have a lot of predictive power
  • Its a greedy algorithm, so the absolute best model may not be found

To solve these problems, I wanted to train over a random forest to see if these problems get addressed, resulting in a lower error rate than the decision tree. We know that Random Forests are a popular approach that addresses the shortcomings of simple trees by resampling the training data. The goal of a random forest is to improve prediction performance and reduce instability. A random forest averages multiple decision trees that were constructed using a subset of the training data and a subset of the attributes on which to split (Source: Piazza Post). So instead of relying on one decision tree, we are relying on the average of many decision trees.

Here is my code to carry out the experiment

Let’s build a Random Forest classifer using quarterly differences after data standardization for years 2014-2016. First, filter to the years of interest and standardize affordability for each region

standardized_df <- predictor_df %>%
  filter(year(time) %in% 2014:2016) %>%
  group_by(RegionID) %>%
  mutate(mean_aff = mean(affordability)) %>%
  mutate(sd_aff = sd(affordability)) %>%
  mutate(z_aff = (affordability - mean_aff) / sd_aff) %>%
  ungroup()

To train our model we need a table with one row per region, and attributes corresponding to differences in quarterly affordability. We will do this in stages, first we turn the tidy dataset into a wide dataset using tidyr::spread then create a dataframe containing the differences we use as features.

wide_df <- standardized_df %>%
  dplyr::select(RegionID, time, z_aff) %>%
  tidyr::spread(time, z_aff)

Now, we turn this into quarterly differences

matrix_1 <- wide_df %>%
  dplyr::select(-RegionID) %>%
  as.matrix() %>%
  .[,-1]

matrix_2 <- wide_df %>%
  dplyr::select(-RegionID) %>%
  as.matrix() %>%
  .[,-ncol(.)]

diff_df <- (matrix_1 - matrix_2) %>%
  magrittr::set_colnames(NULL) %>%
  as_data_frame() %>%
  mutate(RegionID = wide_df$RegionID)

Finally, add the outcome we want to predict from the data frame we created previously.

final_df <- diff_df %>%
  inner_join(outcome_df %>% dplyr::select(RegionID, Direction), by="RegionID") %>%
  mutate(Direction=factor(Direction, levels=c("down", "up")))
final_df

Splitting the data and training it

Now split up the data set into training regions and testing regions (using 80/20 random split).

set.seed(1234)
randomForestTest <- final_df %>%
  group_by(Direction) %>%
  sample_frac(.2) %>%
  ungroup()

randomForestTrain <- final_df %>%
  anti_join(randomForestTest, by="RegionID")

set.seed(1234)
decisionTreeTest <- final_df %>%
  group_by(Direction) %>%
  sample_frac(.2) %>%
  ungroup()

decisionTreeTrain <- final_df %>%
  anti_join(decisionTreeTest, by="RegionID")

Random Forest

Let’s learn the random forest using default parameters.

rf <- randomForest(Direction~., data=randomForestTrain %>% dplyr::select(-RegionID))

print(errorRateDT)

Since the error rate for the decision tree is greater, it seems that the Random Forest gives better predictions for whether mortgage affordability will increase/decrease next year.

Cross Validation

Now, same example, but looking at 10-fold cross-validation to compare a random forest with 500 trees, with a single decision tree. Since this is a smallish dataset, I am using 10-fold cross validation to make the validation sets have more examples and therefore more reliable performance estimates.

First, we create data frame to contain the results of the experiment. That is, for each observation (region) in the training set (rows) we will have attributes for predictions (as continuous values) for both the random forest and decision tree, the observed labels (‘up’ or ‘down’) and index of the cross-validation fold in which the observation was used as a test example. We will then use this data frame to compute error rates, do a hypothesis test for differences in error and to create an ROC curve.

We use the caret::createFolds function to create a stratified 10-fold cross-validation partition. The result is a list of length 10, containing the indices of the examples used for validation in each of the cross-validation folds.

We pipe the result to the purrr::imap function which applies to each list (and it’s index) a function that (a) splits the data into train and test sets, (b) fits the two random forests, and (c) creates a data frame with the values we need.

The result of purrr::imap is a list of data frames, so we pipe it to purrr::reduce to create a single data frame.

set.seed(1234)

result_df <- createFolds(final_df$Direction, k=10) %>%
  
  purrr::imap(function(test_indices, fold_number) {

    train_df <- final_df %>%
      dplyr::select(-RegionID) %>%
      slice(-test_indices)

    test_df <- final_df %>%
      dplyr::select(-RegionID) %>%
      slice(test_indices)
  
    theForest <- randomForest(Direction~., data=train_df, ntree=500)
    theTree <- tree(Direction~., data=train_df)
    
    test_df %>%
      dplyr::select(observedLabel = Direction) %>%
      mutate(fold=fold_number) %>%
      mutate(probabilityPositiveRF = predict(theForest, newdata=test_df, type="prob")[,"up"]) %>%
      mutate(predictedLabelRF = ifelse(probabilityPositiveRF > 0.5, "up", "down")) %>%
      mutate(predictedLabelDT = predict(theTree, type="class", newdata=test_df)) %>%
      mutate(probabilityPositiveDT = ifelse(predictedLabelDT == "up", 1, 0))
}) %>%
  purrr::reduce(bind_rows)
result_df

Now let’s compute error rates for each model on each fold, and do a test for differences in error rate

result_df %>%
  mutate(forestError = observedLabel != predictedLabelRF,
         treeError = observedLabel != predictedLabelDT) %>%
  group_by(fold) %>%
  summarize(big_rf = mean(forestError), small_rf = mean(treeError)) %>%
  tidyr::gather(model, error, -fold) %>%
  lm(error~model, data=.) %>%
  broom::tidy()
##            term  estimate  std.error statistic      p.value
## 1   (Intercept) 0.3886905 0.04121185  9.431522 2.181151e-08
## 2 modelsmall_rf 0.1454365 0.05828236  2.495378 2.252332e-02

We noticed that the p.value is 0.0252332, since the p.value is less than 0.05, we must reject the null hypothesis and conclude that a significant difference does exist.

Auroc Curve

# create a list of true observed labels 
labels <- split(result_df$observedLabel, result_df$fold)

# now create a list of predictions for the first RF and pass it to the ROCR::prediction function
forestPredictions <- split(result_df$probabilityPositiveRF, result_df$fold) %>% prediction(labels)

# do the same for the DT
treePredictions <- split(result_df$probabilityPositiveDT, result_df$fold) %>% prediction(labels)

# compute average AUC for the RF
aucForest <- forestPredictions %>%
  performance(measure="auc") %>%
  slot("y.values") %>% unlist() %>% 
  mean()

# compute average AUC for the DT
aucTree <- treePredictions %>%
  performance(measure="auc") %>%
  slot("y.values") %>% unlist() %>% 
  mean()

# plot the ROC curve for the RF
forestPredictions %>%
  performance(measure="tpr", x.measure="fpr") %>%
  plot(avg="threshold", col="orange", lwd=2)

# plot the ROC curve for the DT
treePredictions %>%
  performance(measure="tpr", x.measure="fpr") %>%
  plot(avg="horizontal", col="blue", lwd=2, add=TRUE)

# add a legend to the plot
legend("bottomright",
       legend=paste(c("big", "small"), "rf, AUC:", round(c(aucForest, aucTree), digits=3)),
       col=c("orange", "blue"))

Interpretation and discussion of results:

  • The confusion matrix for the random forest gave an error rate of 31.25%
  • The confusion matrix for the decision tree gave an error rate of 50.00%

Since the error rate for the decision tree is greater, it seems that the Random Forest gives better predictions for whether mortgage affordability will increase/decrease next year.

Additionally, the AUROC plots support this:

  • The Random Forest AUROC score is 0.583
  • The Decision Tree AUROC score is 0.44
  • The higher Random Forest AUROC score (0.583) indicates that the rate of correct (true positive) classifications is greater than the rate of incorrect (false positive) classifications for the Random Forest, while the lower Decision Tree AUROC score (0.44) indicates otherwise for the Decision Tree.

These two things (confusion matrix and auroc plot) indicate that the Random Forest is indeed better than the Decision Tree because the Random Forest has both a higher AUROC score and a lower error rate than the single Decision Tree, indicating greater predictive performance.

Now that we know the Random Forest has better predictions than the Decision Tree, we must determine if it is significantly better. In our 10-fold cross validation, we noticed that the p.value is 0.0252332. Since the p.value is less than 0.05, we must reject the null hypothesis and conclude that a significant difference does exist between the Random Forest and Decision Tree, in favor of the Random Forest.

In conclusion, this means that a Random Forest is significantly better than a Decision Tree at predictions.
